"vóór 1148","Abt 1117":"circa 1117","1132":"1132","1065":"1065","1120":"1120","1096":"1096","1140":"1140","1194":"1194","1170":"1170","1129":"1129","1117":"1117","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1115":"1115","1224":"1224","1125":"1125","about 1108":"circa 1108","1109":"1109","um 1148":"circa 1148","England":"England","Of, Rayleigh, Essex, England":"Rayleigh, Essex, England"},"en":{"Abt 1117–":"about 1117–Deceased","1109–1140":"1109–1140","1115–Male":"1115–Deceased","1117–Male":"1117–Deceased","1120–1170":"1120–1170","1125–Female":"1125–Deceased","1125–Male":"1125–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1148–1194":"1148–1194","1065–1132":"1065–1132","1096–1129":"1096–1129","before 1148":"before 1148","Abt 1117":"about 1117","1132":"1132","1065":"1065","1120":"1120","1096":"1096","1140":"1140","1194":"1194","1170":"1170","1129":"1129","1117":"1117","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1115":"1115","1224":"1224","1125":"1125","about 1108":"about 1108","1109":"1109","um 1148":"about 1148","England":"England","Of, Rayleigh, Essex, England":"Rayleigh, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Essex","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from the county of Essex, whose name is from Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>Seaxe</i> ‘Saxons’. In England, the surname is now particularly common in Birmingham."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":98,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":107,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Hugh De Essex I was born about 1117, in Rayleigh, Essex, England, his father, Robert of Essex Lord of Rayleigh, was 54 and his mother, Gunnora of Essex, was 23. He married Mrs Hugh De Essex I before 1148, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1117–":"umbes 1117–Surnud","1109–1140":"1109–1140","1115–Male":"1115–Surnud","1117–Male":"1117–Surnud","1120–1170":"1120–1170","1125–Female":"1125–Surnud","1125–Male":"1125–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1148–1194":"1148–1194","1065–1132":"1065–1132","1096–1129":"1096–1129","before 1148":"enne 1148","Abt 1117":"umbes 1117","1132":"1132","1065":"1065","1120":"1120","1096":"1096","1140":"1140","1194":"1194","1170":"1170","1129":"1129","1117":"1117","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1115":"1115","1224":"1224","1125":"1125","about 1108":"umbes 1108","1109":"1109","um 1148":"umbes 1148","England":"England","Of, Rayleigh, Essex, England":"Rayleigh, Essex, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1117–":"noin 1117–Kuollut","1109–1140":"1109–1140","1115–Male":"1115–Kuollut","1117–Male":"1117–Kuollut","1120–1170":"1120–1170","1125–Female":"1125–Kuollut","1125–Male":"1125–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1148–1194":"1148–1194","1065–1132":"1065–1132","1096–1129":"1096–1129","before 1148":"ennen vuotta 1148","Abt 1117":"noin 1117","1132":"1132","1065":"1065","1120":"1120","1096":"1096","1140":"1140","1194":"1194","1170":"1170","1129":"1129","1117":"1117","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1115":"1115","1224":"1224","1125":"1125","about 1108":"noin 1108","1109":"1109","um 1148":"noin 1148","England":"England","Of, Rayleigh, Essex, England":"Rayleigh, Essex, England"},"fr":{"Abt 1117–":"environ 1117–Décédé","1109–1140":"1109–1140","1115–Male":"1115–Décédé","1117–Male":"1117–Décédé","1120–1170":"1120–1170","1125–Female":"1125–Décédée","1125–Male":"1125–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1148–1194":"